    <h1 class="page-title">Bromberg et al. (2011)</h1>

    <div class="infobox">
      <h3 class="infobox-title">Bromberg et al. 2011</h3>
      <table>
        <tr><th>Type:</th><td>Paper (analytic model)</td></tr>
        <tr><th>Educational level:</th><td>Research / Intermediate</td></tr>
        <tr><th>DOI:</th><td>10.1088/0004-637X/740/2/100</td></tr>
      </table>
    </div>

    <p>Bromberg et al. (2011) developed an analytic model describing the interaction of a jet with its environment, deriving scalings for cocoon pressure, jet-head motion, and the conditions under which jets collimate and form recollimation shocks. Peretti et al. (2603.16647) extend this framework into the sub-relativistic regime for particle-acceleration estimates.</p>

    <h2>Why this matters</h2>
    <p>The Bromberg formalism provides a tractable way to predict where standing shocks form and how cocoon pressure evolves—key inputs when coupling hydrodynamics to particle-transport models.</p>

    <h2>See also</h2>
    <ul>
      <li><WikiLink slug="pages/jet-cocoon-systems" text="Jet–Cocoon systems" /></li>
      <li><WikiLink slug="pages/recollimation-shocks" text="Recollimation shocks" /></li>
      <li><WikiLink slug="pages/2603.16647" text="Peretti et al. (2603.16647)" /></li>
    </ul>
  </main>
</Base>